column2: hearing @amyklobuchar announce her candidacy for president of the united states was a very special moment this afternoon! she joins a race that is so important to restore the office of the presidency. i had the opportunity to hear her speak and to meet her in 2017 while attending the @voterunlead training.ğŸ’ªâ¤ï¸ // âœ¨on a very personal note for backstory: i was there to learn how to get women elected. iâ€™d set-up a @gofundme account in which friends and family contributed to get me there
column3: and i was on a partial scholarship chosen by @voterunlead. it was my small way to educate myself on how i can help more women. women supporting women has always been something important to me
column4: but especially that year. i had to feel like i was helping fight against the disturbing behavior and treatment of women from people like trump
column6: and my then most recent employer. i was working at a place earlier that year in which i was wrongfully (and illegally) terminated for speaking up about a man that had sexually harassed me and also worked there. it didnâ€™t matter how he treated me inappropriately and many others. my own supervisor said sheâ€™d felt sexually harassed by him and yet she was the one to tell me i was no longer with the company... as i dealt with that feeling of disappointment and betrayal i channeled it into finding ways to build up other women and create meaningful change. so today brought me back to a time where i was fighting against what was wrongful treatment and how i took action into my hands with the support of loved ones. 2017 was one of the hardest years of my life and yet moments like the @voterunlead conference and hearing @amyklobuchar speak still stay with me not to mention the amazing friendships i made at that conference! // congrats @amyklobuchar on your new journey and i hope we can meet again someday
column7: but until then i look forward to seeing your campaign proceed onward! ğŸ’ªâ¤ï¸ #metoo #metoomovement;;en;#metoo

column1: 39079;instagram;2019-02-11 06:18:53;FALSE;"when those first memories of abuse returned
column2: i stumbled around in a state of denial and shock.  after the dust settled and i began to accept the possibility of a disturbing alternative past
column3: i felt bewildered and unsettled.  i could not get my head around the fact that i had been targeted and chosen for long term abuse.  i would tell myself not to take it personallyâ€”the perpetrator was a sick man and i was a convenient victim.  if it hadnâ€™t been me
column4: it would have been someone else in my place.  then i would inwardly scream
column5: â€œhow can i not take this personally?!?â€ i grieve for that bewildered little girl who felt disposable and unworthy of love and safety.  sadly
column6: this forlorn invisibility was the calm before the storm.  my uncleâ€™s systematic brainwashing had planted the early seeds of shame in my young developing brain.  soon bewilderment would be replaced with a dull and ever-present self-loathing.  the task of chipping away at this gut-deep shame is daunting.  just writing this reminds me to be gentle and patient with my healing.  it takes time.

column5: â€œhow can i not take this personally?!?â€ i grieve for that bewildered little girl who felt disposable and unwohy of love and safety.  sadly
column6: this forlorn invisibility was the calm before the storm.  my uncleâ€™s systematic brainwashing had planted the early seeds of shame in my young developing brain.  soon bewilderment would be replaced with a dull and ever-present self-loathing.  the task of chipping away at this gut-deep shame is daunting.  just writing this reminds me to be gentle and patient with my healing.  it takes time.

column1: at work we have these sessions called ""courageous conversations"" where you share an aspect of diversity you struggle to accept & then hear stories from ppl from that group.  i heard a woman talk about political diversity & her deep bias against trump voters.  i could totally relate! im sure i know some trump folk at work & there may be some here on ig but id rather not know who bc i dont have the ability (yet) to understand
column3: trust them.  i feel like it would be difficult for me to hold them in the same regard as colleagues once i knew. i get along with everyone at work.  i never really have issues with anyone but if i knew that shit id def be looking sideways at them and it could affect our interactions!! ğŸ˜¡

column1: i know this may be extreme thinking... but the whole point of the exercise is that we all hold some form of ugly bias. the notion is to put it on the table... and think about the experiences (usually connected to some fear)  that created the bias.  for me the underlying fear is that they are undercover racists & will harm me and/or other minorities in some way.  i also fear that they lack integrity & would be willing to conduct/ accept unscrupulous behavior for personal gain- which would affect me negatively as their teammate.  is this logical?  maybe

im going to be working a new diversity segment into my programs this year. it will focus on helping leaders navigate & address the crazy issues going on in our country/world.  obviously attitudes like mine are not healthy in the workplace.  i need to learn to deal with my anger for trump folk.  for others
column2: they may be struggling with lgbt understanding

column3: but its my truth.  and there is a powerful phrase that i stole & now like to use- ""its hard to hate up close."" maybe knowing more about the trump folk im working & living among would do me some good.  im willing to try. #loveyourneighbor #diversity";;en;#metoo

all the secrets and lies and dreams - nothing but ashes in the wind.

column1: 39470;instagram;2019-02-10 23:32:35;FALSE;"times up!  iâ€™m sure that this is just the beginning of survivors of sexual assault finding their voices in the southern baptist church.  unfortunately
column2: iâ€™m not at all surprised by this news and iâ€™ve seen way too many women and men treated like they were the problem when they spoke up.  this isnâ€™t just a southern baptist issue.  this is an issue of inflated egos
column3: narcissism and the abuse of power in the church.  where were the real leaders when this was happening?  where was the accountability? this is sick
column4: it is perverse and these actions require a good old fashioned rebuking in jesus name.  enough trying to â€œsave face.â€ i canâ€™t wrap my head around how pastors can stand before their congregations and preach the bible and yet prey on those who come to their churches to experience the hope and grace of god. this grieves the heart of god and should grieve ours too.  i am disgusted and so thankful that this is coming to light.  people have been scared to talk and shamed into silence for far too long.  i pray that survivors find freedom as they stand firm against the oppression of undeserved shame. i am a survivor of sexual assault and i can attest to the spiritual
column5: emotional and psychological pain that occurs for years to come.  i have at times questioned my own faith based on the actions and responses of people who claimed to be representing god.  my assurance comes from knowing that my god is a just god that crushes the oppressor.  he is near to the broken-hearted and he expects his followers to represent him in the same manner.  my faith is in god and not man.  my prayer is that these survivors find healing and that manâ€™s sins do not turn their hearts from god. it is past due for the church to rise up and stand up for truth.  i stand for truth.  i stand with the survivors.

singing a brave song from the heart... in ""the day my soul cried"" yvonne pierre shares a memoir that reads like a song from the heart. the author shares her experiences as a child growing up and as a young adult
column2: leading the reader from tragedy through awakening to joy. yvonne pierre has now created support for parents of children with special needs
column3: which is how i met her
column4: through her ""have ya heard"" radio. i'm so grateful she shared her story with us
column5: and highly recommend it for anyone who is trying to overcome difficult times and find a light in the darkness. she will inspire you. -  review by j.j. brown .

column1: zoey (novelette): a wonderful story... the story of zoey is quite amazing and what i felt while listening to the audiobook is hard to put into words. the story is more focused on claire
column2: zoey's mom. zoey was born with down syndrome and claire did not know how to deal with it and which didn't allow her to become the mother that her daughter needed. but something terrible happened that made claire realize what she has been doing. this would put you through a roller coaster of emotions. this is such a wonderful story that probably a lot of parents
column3: especially those with kids with special needs
column4: would be able to relate to one way or another. i highly recommend everyone to listen to this book. - review by jd .

column2: is one i agonized over. now i understand why.

column1: it took forever to title it
column2: mainly because it meant the secret would be out.

column1: when the title finally came i understood the tear that accidentally appeared as a paint drip.
she (l refer to my pieces as â€˜sheâ€™) is the many moods of someone who has experienced sexual harassment.
the me too movement is finally here! no woman should have to experience sexual harassment on the job!
there were no movements when at my place of work 31 years ago it was rampant. i watched and heard things i cannot repeat.
i was on the receiving end of men of authority in my office harassing me and my coworkers on a daily basis.

column3: i was so exhausted painting it. it took so much out of me.

column1: now i understand the one that is missing is the one that hid
column2: her shame was unbearable. though she is not visible to you. i know she is still there. and there have been women who told me they saw her
column3: perhaps it was themselves they saw. the silent one
column4: the good girl that wonâ€™t tell.

column5: some are coming out from hiding
column6: and some are confident through their brokenness.

column1: and then there is the protagonist of this story

column2: you not going to win.â€™ if you cannot speak it then paint them
column3: paint them all of your sisters!

â€˜there is a crack in everything thatâ€™s how the light gets inâ€™
iâ€™m being the light in this crack of life through my painting.

column1: 39778;instagram;2019-02-10 19:06:06;FALSE;"this speaks volumes to me. about 3 year's ago i was diagnosed with ptsd it stems from a childhood of severe physical and emotional abuse repeated molestation and rape it's wounds that festered over time. i thought i had put it away deep down. but so many things places people would trigger memories. i say this when trying to explain the dark the sorrow the pain my brain my soul is like a huge cluttered library each book filled with chapters of long and not so long ago memories. those memories are some so dark so horrible i don't dare to pull that book out. i have some of the most precious lovely memories those books are reread over and over. yet i broke and was flooded over and over with the nightmares of my past. as i write this i'm in tears and i'm literally shaking. there were things i did in my past to stop the nightmares from visiting me.

in order to start the process of myself becoming free of the many haughts i had to open the books and read those dark chapters. and speak even if my voice shook. it's utter hell at time's but i have to try and deal n learn to cope and set my soul free. it was not my fault. but i thought it was. not anymore. i feel victim of domestic violence far to many times. #notanymore #ptsd #metoo #childhoodsexualabuse #childhoodabuse #domesticviolence #domesticabuse #freeyourself #freeyoursoul #ihadtoreadthosebooks #speakout #speakevenifyourvoiceshakes #beainspiration #letyourvoicebeheard #findfreedom you really can do it. i promise you can. #overcome and remember #notanymore";;en;#notanymore

column1: 39830;instagram;2019-02-10 17:49:43;FALSE;"you know what i am talking about.
getting passed over for partner by the guy that doesn't work as hard and doesn't have kids. .
getting asked by the opposing counsel if you're the court reporter.
getting bullied by a judge because he thinks he can get away with it.
being told by your partner that you need to go to dinner and drinks with an important client and ""be nice to him"".
i get it sister.  i lived it for 20 years.  as you age those idiots will still ask you if you are the court reporter
column2: you will always be left out of the ""inside jokes"" by the male lawyers and there will be always be the asshole who calls you ""sweetheart"". #metoo

column1: so what do you do?  start your own business and become more powerful than they are.
you don't need to be treated like that.  you are intelligent and resourceful.  #changeyourlifenow #legalentrepreneur";;en;#metoo

column1: the story we know of virginia lt. governor justin fairfax is a narrative that
